tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Sept 03, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104idq1665702893497.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/idq1665702893497.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/idq1665702893497.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"idq1665702893497\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Implementing Java Call-in\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body taskbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">\n</p>\n<section><ol class=\"ol steps\"><li class=\"li step\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18317e1_d18318e1_d18319e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Configure Uniface so that it can generate Java wrapper files for Uniface components. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"arf1665702893579.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/arf1665702893579.html\" title=\"Uniface uses the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) to support Java call-in at runtime, and the Java Developer Kit for compiling and packaging generated Java wrapper files. You need to configure Uniface so that it can locate these facilities when required, and you need to enable Java to find the Uniface Java call-in DLLs.\">Configuring Java Call-In</a>.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18320e1_d18321e1_d18322e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"idq1665702893497__p_d35921e1_d35922e1_d35923e1\">Define Java call-in implementations for the\n               Uniface components you want to call from Java. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"bvp1665702771864.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/bvp1665702771864.html\" title=\"The signatures of Uniface components that are called by Java applications must specify a Java component implementation. The signature can then be used to generate Java wrapper classes for the component.\">Defining Java Implementations for Uniface Components</a>. </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18323e1_d18324e1_d18325e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Generate the Java wrapper files and package them into a <span class=\"ph filepath\">.jar</span> file. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"ixk1665702772151.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ixk1665702772151.html\" title=\"The Java code generator produces a set of files from each component signature, plus a batch file and manifest file used to compile the .java files into .class files, and package them into a .jar file.\">Generating and Compiling Java Wrapper Files</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"ogj1665702772082.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ogj1665702772082.html\" title=\"The signatures of Uniface components with a Java call-in implementation are used to generate Java files that enable the Uniface components to be treated as Java objects.\">Generated Files for Java Call-In</a>.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18326e1_d18327e1_d18328e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Import the Uniface-generated wrapper files and the Uniface Java Call-In API into your Java development tool.\n </span>\n</li><li class=\"li step\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18329e1_d18330e1_d18331e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">In your Java development environment, create Java application sources that use the Uniface-supplied classes and APIs to instantiate Uniface components and activate operations on those components.\n </span>\n<ol class=\"ol substeps\" type=\"a\">\n<li class=\"li substep substepexpand\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18332e1_d18333e1_d18334e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Use the <code class=\"ph codeph\">ConfigManagerBean</code> to specify or look up the properties of the Uniface environment in which the Uniface component runs\n .\n </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idq1665702893497__p_d35924e1_d35925e1_d35926e1\">For example, you can specify the Java VM as the Java call handler, specify the assignment and initialization files to use, or set command line switches.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"idq1665702893497__p_d35927e1_d35928e1_d35929e1\">For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"azo1665702893717.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/azo1665702893717.html\" title=\"You can control the environment in which a Uniface component runs by setting some Java properties, either at a general package level or for sub-sets.\">Java Properties for Uniface Call-In</a>. </p>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li substep substepexpand\" id=\"idq1665702893497__li_d18335e1_d18336e1_d18337e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"idq1665702893497__p_d35930e1_d35931e1_d35932e1\">Use the methods available in the Java\n                     Call-in API to call operations on Uniface components, create and delete\n                     occurrences, retrieve and modify data, and so on. For more information, see\n                        <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"pmu1665702894939.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pmu1665702894939.html\" title=\"You can use the Java Call-In API to call the operations of a Uniface component from your Java application and to configure the environment in which the components run.\">Calling Uniface Components from Java</a>. </span>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li></ol></section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2528499\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2528499\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Implementing Java Call-in Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Sept 03, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Implementing Java Call-in Configure Uniface so that it can generate Java wrapper files for Uniface components. For more information, see Configuring Java Call-In . Define Java call-in implementations for the Uniface components you want to call from Java. For more information, see Defining Java Implementations for Uniface Components . Generate the Java wrapper files and package them into a .jar file. For more information, see Generating and Compiling Java Wrapper Files and Generated Files for Java Call-In . Import the Uniface-generated wrapper files and the Uniface Java Call-In API into your Java development tool. In your Java development environment, create Java application sources that use the Uniface-supplied classes and APIs to instantiate Uniface components and activate operations on those components. Use the ConfigManagerBean to specify or look up the properties of the Uniface environment in which the Uniface component runs . For example, you can specify the Java VM as the Java call handler, specify the assignment and initialization files to use, or set command line switches. For more information, see Java Properties for Uniface Call-In . Use the methods available in the Java Call-in API to call operations on Uniface components, create and delete occurrences, retrieve and modify data, and so on. For more information, see Calling Uniface Components from Java . Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}